comments.body:
While simplifying the example a bit, I noticed that this is actually working:

{code:python}
n_columns = 499999
table = pa.table([np.random.randn(1) for _ in range(n_columns)], names=['col' + str(i) for i in range(n_columns)])

from pyarrow import feather
feather.write_feather(table, "test_wide.feather")
result = feather.read_table("test_wide.feather")
{code}

So it seems that it are the "key-value metadata" that are causing the issue (coming from the pandas->arrow conversion). So this is failing:


{code:python}
table = pa.table(pd.DataFrame(np.random.randn(1, n_columns), columns=['col' + str(i) for i in range(n_columns)]))

feather.write_feather(table, "test_wide_pandas.feather")
result = feather.read_table("test_wide_pandas.feather")
{code}

but this is working again (when removing the pandas metadata):

{code:python}
table2 = table.replace_schema_metadata()

feather.write_feather(table2, "test_wide_pandas2.feather")
result = feather.read_table("test_wide_pandas2.feather")
{code}

I am not sure that I am hitting the 2GB FlatBufffer limit as that would imply that each column (assuming we would have a 1 million columns) would occupy more than 2kb of space.

It seems more likely to me that I hit the max_depth = 64 or  max_tables = 1000000 limit

According to https://groups.google.com/g/flatbuffers/c/JtDGnBPx9is, it seems like these parameters are changeable:
{code:c++}
    /// To expand the capacity of a single buffer, _max_tables is set to 10000000
    flatbuffers::uoffset_t _max_depth = 64;
    flatbuffers::uoffset_t _max_tables = 10000000;
    flatbuffers::Verifier verifier(buf, bufsize, _max_depth, _max_tables);
    OK = OK && grl::flatbuffer::VerifyKUKAiiwaStatesBuffer(verifier);
{code}
